statement.p:
Consider the explicitly defined sequence x = (10 \cdot \frac{1}{2^k})_{k=1}^{\infty}
and the sequence y=(y_n)_{n=1}^{\infty} defined recursively
with an initial value y_1 = 5 and iteration y_{n} = \frac{1}{2}y_{n-1}
for n=2, 3, \ldots.
Show that x and y represent the same sequence.

solution.p:
We next compare the recurrence relations.
We know that y has projection function f: y_{n-1} \mapsto y_n = \frac{1}{2}y_{n-1}.
We need to show that x satisfies the same relation, x_k = \frac{1}{2} x_{k-1}.
Using the explicit formula for x, we compute both sides of the recurrence equation and show they are equivalent.

   x_k &= 10 \cdot \frac{1}{2^k} 
   \frac{1}{2} x_{k-1} &= \frac{1}{2} \cdot 10 \cdot \frac{1}{2^{(k-1)}}
   &= 10 \cdot \frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{1}{2^{(k-1)}}
   &= 10 \cdot \frac{1}{2^{(k-1)+1}}
   &= 10 \cdot \frac{1}{2^{k}}

Comparing the formulas, we see that x_k = \frac{1}{2} x_{k-1}.

statement.p:
         Evaluate the following sums. 


\displaystyle \sum_{k=3}^{7} [2k+3] 

\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^{4} \frac{1}{k^2+k}

li.p:
The sum \displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^{4} \frac{1}{k^2+k} 
involves an increment sequence \displaystyle b_k=\frac{1}{k^2+k}. 
The index values involved go from 1 to 4 so that we find 

   \sum_{k=1}^{4} \frac{1}{k^2+k} &= 
  \frac{1}{1^1+1} + \frac{1}{2^2+2} + \frac{1}{3^2+3} + \frac{1}{4^2+4} 
   &= \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{6} + \frac{1}{12} + \frac{1}{20} 
   &= \frac{30}{60} + \frac{10}{60} + \frac{5}{60} + \frac{3}{60} 
   &= \frac{48}{60} = \frac{4}{5}.

statement.p:
Write the accumulation sequence z = (z_n)_{n=0}^{\infty} 
with initial value z_0=4 and an increment sequence a = (3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, \ldots)
as a summation with an explicit formula for the increments.
